                <head>188. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On September 3, 1969, <persName corresp="#p_MRM1">Richard Moose</persName> of the
                    National Security Council staff commented on behalf of the National Security
                    Council on several legislative referrals from the Bureau of the Budget (<gloss
                        target="#t_BOB1">BOB</gloss>) in a memorandum to J.F.C. Hyde, Assistant
                    Director for Legislative Reference (<gloss target="#t_BOB1">BOB</gloss>). With
                    regard to the draft Romanian Trade Act of 1969, <persName corresp="#p_MRM1"
                        >Moose</persName> noted: “The President has decided that for present he has
                    sufficient latitude to pursue the goal of improved trade relations with the
                    countries of Eastern Europe without seeking any change in the Export Control Act
                    or further authority to extend <gloss target="#t_MFN1">MFN</gloss> treatment.”
                    (National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential
                    Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 703, Country
                    Files—Europe, Romania, Vol. III Jul 1970–Dec 1971)</p>
            </div>
